  preparation:{label:"Preparation Rules",icon:"📋",color:"#06b6d4",note:"How you prepare and store food matters as much as what you eat. These rules are as important as the food lists.",subcats:{"The Freshness Rule":["Histamine rises rapidly in cooked protein — refrigerate within 30 minutes, consume within 24 hours","Freeze meat immediately after purchase if not cooking same day","Thaw in refrigerator, never at room temperature","Cook from frozen directly when possible","When in doubt, throw it out"],"Cooking Methods (best to worst)":["Steaming — lowest histamine formation","Boiling (discard water)","Pressure cooking (short time)","Baking or roasting — moderate","Grilling — higher","Slow cooking — highest for meat and fish — avoid","Fermentation — highest of all"],"Reading Labels":["Avoid: natural flavors (often contain histamine or glutamate)","Avoid: yeast extract, autolyzed yeast, hydrolyzed protein","Avoid: citric acid (often triggers reactions)","Avoid: artificial colors — tartrazine, Red 40, Blue 1","Avoid: sodium benzoate, potassium sorbate, sulfites (E220-228)","Avoid: MSG and glutamates"]}},
